<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-direct-deposit-pending-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Direct deposit pending,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qb-help-direct-deposit-pending-in-brief-text">A payroll direct deposit is the electronic transfer that moves net pay from your funding account into each employee&rsquo;s bank account. When it shows &ldquo;pending&rdquo; or hasn&rsquo;t landed, it usually means the deposit has been submitted but hasn&rsquo;t posted yet &mdash; most often because direct deposit has a <em>lead time</em> and a cutoff, so it processes on the scheduled deposit date rather than instantly. &ldquo;Pending&rdquo; before that date is normal. Other times it&rsquo;s a funding issue, a bank holiday or weekend shifting the date, an unverified bank account, an Intuit risk or security review, or incorrect employee bank details.</p>
      <p>Here&rsquo;s the honest part. The direct-deposit <em>processing</em> itself &mdash; the debit from your funding account, the timeline, any funding hold, and any risk review &mdash; is part of Intuit&rsquo;s payroll service. An independent firm can&rsquo;t reach into that to release a deposit or lift a hold; if the deposit is held or under review, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve. What an independent ProAdvisor firm <em>can</em> do is everything around it: confirming the setup is correct, checking that the funding was in place, verifying the bank details, and reconciling the payroll in the books once it posts so your records are clean and tie out.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

